# Lab Name
Reflected DOM XSS

## Vulnerability
Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) – Reflected DOM-Based XSS

## Objective
Exploit a DOM-based XSS vulnerability and execute JavaScript in the victim's browser.

## Entry Point
URL parameter processed by client-side JavaScript

## Exploitation Type
DOM-Based XSS

## Methodology
1. Open the lab and inspect the application's functionality

2. Observe that user input is read from the URL

3. Notice that client-side JavaScript processes the input and inserts it into the page

4. Identify a vulnerable DOM sink where the input is reflected without proper sanitization

5. Craft a malicious payload

6. Append the payload to the vulnerable URL parameter

7. Load the modified URL

8. The browser processes the client-side script

9. Observe that the injected JavaScript executes successfully

## Payload Used

<svg onload=alert(1)>

## Result
Successfully executed arbitrary JavaScript through a reflected DOM-based XSS vulnerability.

## Impact
- Execution of arbitrary JavaScript
- Session hijacking
- Cookie theft
- Phishing attacks
- Account compromise
- Manipulation of page content

## Mitigation
- Sanitize and validate all user-controlled input
- Avoid inserting untrusted data into DOM sinks
- Use safe APIs such as textContent instead of innerHTML
- Implement Content Security Policy (CSP)
- Perform context-aware output encoding

## Learning
DOM-based XSS occurs when client-side JavaScript processes untrusted input and inserts it into the DOM without proper sanitization.
Unlike traditional reflected XSS, the vulnerability exists entirely in the browser and may not be visible in the server response.
